-- South African Stocks: Afrox, Anglo, ArcelorMittal, Old Mutual
-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 2011-12-15T15:43:34Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-15/south-african-stocks-anglo-american-bhp-harmony-old-mutual.html
The  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index 
advanced for the first time in six days, gaining 279.67, or 0.9
percent, to 32,006.70 by the close in Johannesburg, reducing
losses for the week to 1.9 percent.  The index has weakened 0.4 percent this year.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today. Stock symbols follow company names.  African Oxygen Ltd. (AFX)  ,  South Africa ’s largest
producer of industrial gases, rose 0.6 percent to 17.10 rand.
Basic earnings per share for the 12 months through December are
expected to be at least 20 percent higher than a year earlier,
the company said in a trading update.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  , the mining company that makes
up more than 9 percent of the benchmark  stock index , gained the
most in two weeks, climbing 1.7 percent to 302.15 rand. Copper
rose for the first time in four days on speculation yesterday’s
5.1 percent plunge was overdone given forecasts for demand in
 China , the biggest buyer.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BIL)  , the world’s biggest miner,
advanced for the first day in seven, adding 1.2 percent to
241.90 rand.  ArcelorMittal South Africa Ltd. (ACL)  ,  Africa ’s largest
steelmaker, rose the most since April 2009, surging 9.5 percent
to 66 rand. The company and  Kumba Iron Ore Ltd. (KIO)   won a
bid to overturn the award of a right over the country’s largest
iron-ore mine to a company whose owners include a business
partner of President Jacob Zuma’s son.  Kumba added 0.8 percent to 500 rand.  Harmony Gold Mining Co. (HAR)  , Africa’s third-largest
gold producer, advanced for the first time in six days, adding
0.4 percent to 101.66 rand. The company said it has restarted
mining activities at its Hidden Valley mine in  Papua New Guinea 
after operations were temporarily suspended following an
earthquake.  Metair Investments Ltd. (MTA)  , a company that
manufactures motor vehicle components, gained 1 percent to 18.99
rand. Earnings per share for the 12 months through December will
be at least 20 percent higher than last year, the company said
in a trading statement.  Old Mutual Plc (OML)  , South Africa’s largest insurer and
the third-biggest insurer in the U.K., rose the most since March
2009, climbing 12 percent to 16.24 rand. The company plans to
sell its Nordic business, excluding Finland, for 2.1 billion
pounds ($3.3 billion) to Skandia Liv, it said in a regulatory
filing.  To contact the reporter on this story:
